<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-cones" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Cones</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_m235p6p6">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_d1vixixd">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_0jh6o5ad">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rqlecvte">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_c48jtolm">
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_43lii7pa">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_863ouo9t">Calculate the surface area of composite solids</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ixl0wcpk">Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kg4vf9zp" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_fn7rg77e">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a90gqn5u" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_myenvbaf">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <introduction xml:id="auto_ckpgjy7r" component="lesson-plan">
            <p xml:id="auto_3nz33peb"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_ds8hh05f">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6gii4fm3">
                        <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a cone as a three-dimensional geometric shape with a circular base and a curved surface that tapers to a point called the apex. State the formula for the surface area of a cone: <m>\pi r^2 + \pi r \ell</m>. Understand the relationship between height, radius, and slant height using the Pythagorean theorem.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w30f4n3j">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2gebwyp5">
                        <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the surface area of cones using the formula. Determine the slant height using the Pythagorean theorem. Identify the faces that make up a cone and calculate their individual areas.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qo26rjcq">
                    <p xml:id="auto_kl8u5jnj">
                        <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving surface areas of cones, such as conical tents, containers, ice cream cones, traffic cones, funnels, and party hats.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_ljqntyxz">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/surface-area-of-cones.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_zcyycu4i">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/step-by-step-guide_surface-area-of-cones.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_jswe6aju">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bm77zf4s">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Groups of 3–4
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_anpwnc3f">
            <alert>Activity:</alert> Deriving the Surface Area Formula for Cones
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_c2xc1u5p">
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_a2cfjpsm"><p xml:id="auto_kybgljml"><q>What is a cone?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_n3g88wq3"><p xml:id="auto_feoxk4g7"><q>What faces make up a cone?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_cia2lwbf"><p xml:id="auto_fr62pkvb"><q>How is the curved surface related to a sector of a circle?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_x09vbjno"><p xml:id="auto_yk8l29fd"><q>How do we find the slant height if we know the height and radius?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_r7zdo9fi"><p xml:id="auto_5i90b87e"><q>What is the formula for the surface area of a cone?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_06mikz6n">
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_i3epzodj"><p xml:id="auto_uysecjyo">Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to identify the faces of a cone.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_abnn4kly"><p xml:id="auto_bv0pif55">Ask probing questions: <q>What shapes make up the cone? How can we find the area of the curved surface?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_aexenb6v"><p xml:id="auto_hj83li9y">For struggling groups: <q>Let us start by finding the area of the base. Then think about how the curved surface can be unfolded.</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_99raeyvr"><p xml:id="auto_akonmqqe">For early finishers: <q>Can you derive the formula for a cone without a base (just the curved surface)?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_n6yt2rs3"><p xml:id="auto_bu1sezko">Guide students to articulate: <q>The surface area of a cone equals the base area plus the curved surface area.</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jh4mx1h5"><p xml:id="auto_1ezrfans">Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_dzvbnx3y">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_ld0qxmxh">
                
            </p>
        
            <p xml:id="auto_w0uoo4go">
                If a cone has a height of h and a base of radius r, show that the surface area is: <m>\pi r^2 + \pi r \sqrt{r^2 + h^2}</m>
            </p>

       
            <p xml:id="auto_7l04a150">
              Sketch and label the cone
            </p>
            <image width="100%">
            <latex-image label="cone_net">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define colors
                    \definecolor{circlecolor}{RGB}{255, 140, 0}  % Orange
                    \definecolor{semicirclecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light Blue

                    % Left Figure: Circle on top of a properly aligned semicircle
                    \fill[circlecolor] (0,3) circle (1); % Orange circle

                    % Properly positioned semicircle
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) arc[start angle=180, end angle=0, radius=2] -- cycle; 

                    % Outline for clarity
                    \draw (-2,0) arc[start angle=180, end angle=0, radius=2];

                    % Circle radius
                    \draw[dashed] (0,3) -- (1,3) node[midway, above] {\small $r$};

                    % Semicircle base markings
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (2,0) node[midway, below] {\small $\ell$};
                    \draw[-&gt;] (-2,-0.3) -- (-0.2,0);
                    \draw[-&gt;] (2,-0.3) -- (0.2,0);

                    % Right Figure: Cone
                    \fill[circlecolor] (5,2) ellipse (1.2 and 0.4); % Orange ellipse (top of cone)
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (6.2,1.6) -- (5,0) -- (3.8,1.6) -- cycle; % Light blue cone body

                    % Cone labels
                    \draw[dashed] (5,0) -- (5,2) node[midway, right] {\small $h$}; % Height line
                    \draw[dashed] (5,2) -- (6.2,1.6) node[midway, above] {\small $r$}; % Radius line
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (3.8,1.6) -- (5,0) node[midway, left] {\small $\ell$}; % Slant height

                    % Formula checkbox

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p xml:id="auto_myd5uo73">
                Identify the faces that make up the cone
            </p>
           <sidebyside widths="35% 30%"> 
            <image width="40%">
               <latex-image label="cone-sketch">
                 \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \definecolor{circlecolor}{RGB}{255, 140, 0}  % Orange
                    \definecolor{semicirclecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light Blue
                    \draw[thick,fill=semicirclecolor] (0,0) --(2,3) --(4,0) --cycle;
                    \draw[dashed](2,0) --(2,3);
                    \draw[thin] (1.8,0) --(1.8,0.2) --(2,0.2);
                    \node at (2.2,1.){h};
                    \node at (3,-0.3){r};

                \end{tikzpicture}
               </latex-image>
               </image>
               <image width="50%">
               <latex-image label="cone-stkeches">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \definecolor{circlecolor}{RGB}{255, 140, 0}  % Orange
                    \definecolor{semicirclecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light Blue

                     % Draw the entire cone with one uniform color
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7) -- (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7) -- cycle;
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) -- (0,4) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the base ellipse
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7);
                    \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7);
                    
                    % Draw the cone's sides
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (0,4);
                    \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (0,4);
                    
                    % Draw the height
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                    \node[left] at (0,2) {h};
                    
                    % Draw the radius
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \node[below] at (1,0) {r};
                \end{tikzpicture}
               </latex-image>
               </image>
              </sidebyside> 
               <p xml:id="auto_954tj0um">
                The cone has two faces: the base and the faces makig up a wall. The base is a circle of radius r and the walls can be opened
                out to a semi-circle
               </p>
               <image width ="40%">
            <latex-image label="faces-of-a-cone">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[]
                   % Define colors
                    \definecolor{circlecolor}{RGB}{255, 140, 0}  % Orange
                    \definecolor{semicirclecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light Blue
                    % Draw the sector representing the curved surface of the cone
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (0,0) -- (-2.5,2.5) arc (150:390:2.5) -- cycle;
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (-2.5,2.5);
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (1.85,2.5);
                    \draw[thick] (-2.5,2.5) arc (150:390:2.5);
                    
                    % Draw the base circle so its top touches the bottom of the sector
                    \fill[circlecolor] (0,-2.7) circle (1.5);
                    \draw[thick] (0,-2.7) circle (1.5);
                    
                    % Indicate the radius of the base
                    \draw[dashed] (0,-2.7) -- (1.5,-2.7);
                    \node[above] at (0.75,-2.5) {r};
                    
                    % Indicate the slant height of the sector
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,2.7);
                    \node[left] at (0,1.25) {h};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p xml:id="auto_u5l6d1wn">
                This curved surface can be cut into many thin triangles with height close to a (where <m> \ell</m> is the slant height). The
                area of these triangles or sectors can be summed as follow;
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5fj4chtz">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times \text{base} \times \text{height of a small triangle}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac {1}{2} \times 2 \pi r \times \ell </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi r \ell </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3wmgowzr">
                <m> \ell </m> can be calculated using the pythagorean theorem.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hkrlay8a">
                <m> \ell = \sqrt{r^2 + h^2}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_2qsm5qhc">
                Calculate the area of the circular base 
                <m> C_1 = \pi r^2</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3ile906h">
                Calculate the area of the curved walls
                <m> C_2 = \pi r \ell</m>
                <m> = \pi r \sqrt{r^2 + h^2}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3gwoqs5s">
                To find the surface area we sum up all the areas that is:
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_6rcs756k">
                <md>
                    <mrow>A = \amp C_1 + C_2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp  \pi r^2  + \pi r \sqrt{r^2 + h^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \pi (r + \sqrt{r^2 + h^2})</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_tcnxiy4p">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_96r26s4l">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Whole class
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_otsfbtgn">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> After students have completed the anchor activity and shared their findings, formalise the formula for finding the surface area of a cone. Emphasise the difference between height and slant height, and how the Pythagorean theorem connects them.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hcpjpg1b">
            <alert>Prompting Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_qy5phdg5"><p xml:id="auto_txti2q9m"><q>What is the difference between a cone and a cylinder?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g9w3ec35"><p xml:id="auto_mcylx3l0"><q>Why must we add the base area to the curved surface area?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7ws0sbkv"><p xml:id="auto_6isszcam"><q>Are the height and slant height the same? Why not?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_idmse47k"><p xml:id="auto_guh7xdoj"><q>Can you use the height directly in the surface area formula?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5tkexlnh">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row>
                <cell><alert>Misconception</alert></cell>
                <cell><alert>Clarification</alert></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>A cone is the same as a cylinder</cell>
                <cell>No, a cone has a circular base and tapers to a point, while a cylinder has two parallel circular bases.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>I only need to find the curved surface area</cell>
                <cell>No, you must add the base area to the curved surface area for the total surface area.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>The height and slant height are the same</cell>
                <cell>No, the slant height is the distance along the curved surface from the apex to the base edge, while the height is the perpendicular distance from the apex to the base.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>I can use the height directly in the formula</cell>
                <cell>No, you must use the slant height, which can be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem: <m>\ell = \sqrt{r^2 + h^2}</m>.</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_gmjudxxu">
        The <m>\textbf{net of a cone} </m> is a two-dimensional representation of the three-dimensional shape of the cone. 
        It is made up of the curved surface of the cone laid out flat, so that you can see the shape of the cone. 
        The net of a cone is useful for visualizing the shape of the cone and for calculating its surface area and volume.
    </p>
   

    <insight xml:id="auto_neu180yw">
        <p xml:id="auto_wv2421se">
            <term>What is a Cone?</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_60dblhp3">
            A cone is a three-dimensional geometric shape with a circular base and a curved surface that tapers to a point called the apex.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_w8szninu">
            <term>Net of a Cone:</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0fiyimus">
           The net of a cone is a two-dimensional representation of the three-dimensional shape. It consists of: 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8fvnfr7l">
            <ol marker="(a.)">
                <li xml:id="auto_fsyciguq">
                    <p xml:id="auto_z2t45eg1">
                        A circular base
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_we1a4es9">
                    <p xml:id="auto_hgy0ticz">
                        A curved surface that can be laid out flat (sector of a circle)
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bfpn6uch">
            <term>Formula:</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8ha545lz">
            Surface Area of a Cone <m>= \pi\times r^2 + \pi\times r \times l</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_mpmpubav">
            where:
            <ol marker="(i)">
                <li xml:id="auto_yg6csn5m">
                    <p xml:id="auto_xydq6cec">
                        <m>r</m> is the radius of the base
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g7zwerhr">
                    <p xml:id="auto_eunczgxi">
                        <m>l</m> is the slant height
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_r52o51w2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_5cuaq6zp">
                        <m>l = \sqrt{r^2 + h^2}</m> using Pythagorean theorem
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_dtw00xy2">
            <term>Alternative form:</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gcnl630c">
            Surface Area  <m>= \pi\times r^2 + \pi \times r \times \sqrt{r^2 + h^2}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m4qs3hyc">
          Surface Area  <m>= \pi r (r + \sqrt{r^2 + h^2})</m>  
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cdqnjg4u">
            <term>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</term>
        </p>
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Misconception</cell>
                <cell>Clarification</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>A cone is the same as a cylinder</cell>
                <cell> No, a cone has a circular base and tapers to a point, while a cylinder has two parallel circular bases</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>I only need to find the curved surface area</cell>
                <cell>No, you must add the base area to the curved surface area for the total surface area</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>The height and slant height are the same</cell>
                <cell> No, the slant height is the distance along the curved surface from the apex to the base edge, while the height is the perpendicular distance from the apex to the base</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>I can use the height directly in the formula</cell>
                <cell>No, you must use the slant height, which can be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem if you know the height and radius</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        
    </insight>

 <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_pl3co0tm">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qlcc81ft">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual, then pairs to compare
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_pq1bpaxl">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Walk learners through the worked example that follows. After presenting the solution, have learners attempt the exercise questions independently. Circulate to check for understanding and address any difficulties.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_cfxxv132">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_pct1qet1">
                Given a cone with the radius <m>r = \, 14\, \text{cm} </m> and an angle of <m>\angle 60^\circ</m>. Find the surface area of the cone.

            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_c9b0z4co">
                 <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of sector A}= \amp \frac{ \theta }{360^\circ} \pi r^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{60}{360^\circ} \times\frac{22}{7}\times14\times14 </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp102.67 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of circle B}= \amp\pi r^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp\frac{22}{7} \times14 \, \text{cm} \times14\, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp616 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text {Surface area}= \amp102.67 \, \text{cm}^2+616 \, \text{cm}^2  </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 718.67 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md> 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>  
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_7fb2ns32">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_r7y07y0f">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_p2qztudz">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Students complete the following exercise questions individually as an exit ticket. Collect responses to check understanding.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_fndu78aw">
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_frd8fyi1">
                    <p xml:id="auto_swpi86y3">
                        Base area <m>= \pi \times 5^2 = 78.54</m> cm<m>^2</m>. Curved surface area <m>= \pi \times 5 \times 12 = 188.50</m> cm<m>^2</m>. Total surface area <m>= 78.54 + 188.50 = 267.04</m> cm<m>^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_r9i7rhwj">
                    <p xml:id="auto_4spfrhst">
                        Radius <m>= 16 \div 2 = 8</m> cm. Slant height <m>= \sqrt{8^2 + 15^2} = \sqrt{289} = 17</m> cm. Base area <m>= \pi \times 8^2 = 201.06</m> cm<m>^2</m>. Curved surface area <m>= \pi \times 8 \times 17 = 427.26</m> cm<m>^2</m>. Total surface area <m>= 201.06 + 427.26 = 628.32</m> cm<m>^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_19af07q9">
                    <p xml:id="auto_behsx23a">
                        Curved surface area only (no base) <m>= \pi \times 10 \times 18 = 565.49</m> cm<m>^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lm1dudu7">
                    <p xml:id="auto_x1ing1pz">
                        Using <m>\text{SA} = \pi r^2 + \pi r \ell</m>: <m>314 = \pi(10)^2 + \pi(10)\ell</m>. Solving: <m>314 - 100\pi = 10\pi \ell</m>, so <m>\ell = \frac{314 - 100\pi}{10\pi}</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hgxeg2vn">
                    <p xml:id="auto_l54cdhlw">
                        Curved surface area only (no base) <m>= \pi \times 4.2 \times 7.5 \approx 98.96</m> m<m>^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_9ecucdn0">
        <m>\textbf{Exercise}</m>
    </p> 
        <p xml:id="auto_7jn688wv">
        1. A circular cone has a base radius of 5 cm and a slant height of 12 cm. Calculate the total surface area of the cone, including both the curved surface and the circular base
    </p>  
    <image width="40%">
               <latex-image label="cone-stkeches-three">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \definecolor{circlecolor}{RGB}{255, 140, 0}  % Orange
                    \definecolor{semicirclecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light Blue

                     % Draw the entire cone with one uniform color
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7) -- (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7) -- cycle;
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) -- (0,4) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the base ellipse
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7);
                    \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7);
                    
                    % Draw the cone's sides
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (0,4);
                    \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (0,4);
                    
                    % Draw the height
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                    \node[left] at (0,2) {12 cm};
                    
                    % Draw the radius
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \node[below] at (1,0) {5 cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
               </latex-image>
               </image> 
          <p xml:id="auto_qhnmtaq1">
                    2. A cone is constructed with a base diameter of 16 cm and a height of 15 cm. Before finding the total surface area, determine the slant height of the cone using the Pythagorean theorem. Then, calculate the complete surface area.
                </p> 
    <image width="40%">
               <latex-image label="cone-stkeches-two">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \definecolor{circlecolor}{RGB}{255, 140, 0}  % Orange
                    \definecolor{semicirclecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light Blue

                     % Draw the entire cone with one uniform color
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7) -- (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7) -- cycle;
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) -- (0,4) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the base ellipse
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7);
                    \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7);
                    
                    % Draw the cone's sides
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (0,4);
                    \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (0,4);
                    
                    % Draw the height
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                    \node[left] at (0,2) {15 cm};
                    
                    % Draw the radius
                    \draw[dashed] (-2,0) -- (2,0);
                    \node[below] at (1,0) {16 cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
               </latex-image>
               </image> 
               
     
    <p xml:id="auto_4ra7kuzz">
        3. A conical container, open at the top, is made of metal and has a base radius of 10 cm and a slant height of 18 cm. Determine the total metal sheet required to construct this container, excluding the base.
    </p>  
    <p xml:id="auto_dxowh27y">
        4. The total surface area of a cone is given as 314 cm², and its base radius is 10 cm. Using the surface area formula, determine the slant height of the cone.
    </p>   
    <image width="40%">
               <latex-image label="cone-stkeches-one">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \definecolor{circlecolor}{RGB}{255, 140, 0}  % Orange
                    \definecolor{semicirclecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light Blue

                     % Draw the entire cone with one uniform color
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7) -- (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7) -- cycle;
                    \fill[semicirclecolor] (-2,0) -- (0,4) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the base ellipse
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7);
                    \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7);
                    
                    % Draw the cone's sides
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (0,4);
                    \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (0,4);
                    
                    % Draw the height
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                    \node[left] at (0,2) {S.A = $314 \, cm^2$};
                    
                    % Draw the radius
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \node[below] at (1,0) {10 cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
               </latex-image>
               </image> 
     
    <p xml:id="auto_qccow8wj">
        5. A conical tent made of waterproof fabric has a radius of 4.2 m and a slant height of 7.5 m. If the tent does not have a base, calculate the area of fabric required to cover the tent completely.
    </p>                                                        
        <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />

